data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

All that manual `Expression.Call`/`Expression.Lambda` code won't compile. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression tree construction needed — conditionals work directly inside the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Duplicate property names across complex types are now uniquified.** Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` will get auto-generated names like `ShippingAddress_Street1` and `BillingAddress_Street2`. A migration will be generated to rename the columns.

**b) Nested complex types use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`; it's now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix:** Pin the old column names explicitly to avoid a breaking migration:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, a =>
        {
            a.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Alternatively, generate and review the migration — if the rename is acceptable, just apply it.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL for logging):

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add the `string logCommandText` parameter to **every** method you implement on this interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
